                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Hyderabad, Aug. 16: The Andhra Pradesh government has extended a ban on the CPI (Maoist) for another year under the Andhra Pradesh Public Security Act, 1992, which will also cover six frontal organisations of the outfit.          
	The decision came even as senior intelligence and CRPF officers said four MI-16 helicopters fitted with multi-barrel guns that can fire 60,000 rounds per minute were being kept on standby in Maoist-infested Dandakaranya and north Telangana.                  
	New Delhi: The CBI arrested fugitive former MP Pappu Yadav, sentenced for life for the murder of CPM legislator Ajit Sarkar, on Monday from a Gurgaon hospital following a Supreme Court prod. Pappu was sentenced in February 2008 for the June 1998 murder of Sarkar but was granted bail early this year by Patna High Court.                  
	Lucknow: A 50-year-old farmer who was injured in Saturday nights police firing near Aligarh, died on Sunday taking the toll to three in a fight over land. Devendra Kumar lost two acres for a proposed Rs 10,000-crore eight-lane Yamuna Expressway and had joined other farmers in a protest for higher compensation.                  
	 Calcutta: Airline Deccan Charter on Monday announced the launch of its daily services between Calcutta and Jamshedpur from Tuesday. The airline plans to start daily flights to Cooch Behar within 10 days, once it gets security clearance from the Airports Authority of India. The fare for a one-way trip to Jamshedpur will be Rs 4,500.
                                                                                                                                              
